<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1437,1077,1572]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,300,1329,1356]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Habitat:</emphasis>
restricted to chemosynthetic areas, found at hydrothermal vents and methane cold seeps, usually in association with deep-sea mytilid beds (
<bibRefCitation author="Segonzac, M." box="[599,872,1365,1392]" firstAuthor="St ˆ hr" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" pagination="383 - 402" refId="ref201413" refString="St ˆ hr, S. &amp; Segonzac, M. (2005) Deep-sea ophiuroids (Echinodermata) from reducing and non-reducing environments in the North Atlantic Ocean. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom, 85 (2), 383 - 402. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0025315405011318 h" type="journal article" year="2005">St̂hr &amp; Segonzac 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1437,1077,1572]" box="[199,932,1401,1428]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,357,1402,1428]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Larval stage:</emphasis>
probable planktotrophic (
<bibRefCitation author="Segonzac, M." box="[648,920,1401,1428]" firstAuthor="St ˆ hr" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" pagination="383 - 402" refId="ref201413" refString="St ˆ hr, S. &amp; Segonzac, M. (2005) Deep-sea ophiuroids (Echinodermata) from reducing and non-reducing environments in the North Atlantic Ocean. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom, 85 (2), 383 - 402. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0025315405011318 h" type="journal article" year="2005">St̂hr &amp; Segonzac 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1437,1077,1572]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,1438,1464]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Remarks:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[324,548,1438,1464]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiuridae" genus="Ophioctenella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="acies">
<emphasis box="[324,548,1438,1464]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Ophioctenella acies</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be the only echinoderm species restricted to active vent sites known to occur in the 
<collectingRegion box="[327,410,1474,1500]" country="Portugal" name="Acores" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Azores</collectingRegion>
. In one of the few echinoderm studies from deep-sea reducing environments in the North Atlantic, 
<bibRefCitation author="Segonzac, M." box="[257,546,1509,1536]" firstAuthor="St ˆ hr" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" pagination="383 - 402" refId="ref201413" refString="St ˆ hr, S. &amp; Segonzac, M. (2005) Deep-sea ophiuroids (Echinodermata) from reducing and non-reducing environments in the North Atlantic Ocean. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom, 85 (2), 383 - 402. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0025315405011318 h" type="journal article" year="2005">St̂hr &amp; Segonzac (2005)</bibRefCitation>
identify several animals of 
<taxonomicName box="[863,957,1510,1536]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiuridae" genus="Ophioctenella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="acies">
<emphasis box="[863,883,1510,1536]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">O</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[899,957,1511,1536]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">acies</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Lucky Strike, but found this species conspicuously absent from hydrothermal vents of Menez Gwen.
</paragraph>
